No it&#x27;s a good point actually, and it pays to know your context.  Frankly, looking at the 118 lines in assert.h, it does considerably more than I really need.<p>Instead of this:<p><pre><code>  assert(buf->pos < buf->str->len);
</code></pre>
I could just do this instead:<p><pre><code>  if (buf->pos >= buf->str->len) die(&quot;bad pos&quot;);
</code></pre>
If the die message is unique, I don&#x27;t really need to include __FILE__, __LINE__, and the expression itself in it.<p>I could even do this, though it&#x27;s probably overkill for something that should never happen anyway:<p><pre><code>  if (buf->pos >= buf->str->len)
      die(&quot;bad pos %d %d&quot;, buf->pos, buf->str->len);</code></pre>
